## PAGINATION
- List endpoints MUST be paginated. Never return unbounded arrays.
- Use cursor-based pagination for large or real-time datasets:

```json
// âś… GOOD â€” cursor pagination
GET /v1/orders?cursor=eyJpZCI6MTIzfQ&limit=50

{
  "data": [...],
  "nextCursor": "eyJpZCI6MTczfQ",
  "hasMore": true
}

// âťŚ BAD â€” offset pagination breaks on inserts and has O(n) DB cost
GET /v1/orders?page=5&pageSize=50
```

## RESPONSE SHAPE
- Successful responses wrap data in a `data` key for list endpoints.
- Always include `createdAt` and `updatedAt` timestamps on resources.
- Do NOT leak internal IDs (auto-increment integers). Use UUIDs or opaque string IDs.

```json
// âś… GOOD
{ "data": { "id": "usr_01HX...", "email": "alice@example.com", "createdAt": "2024-01-15T12:00:00Z" } }

// âťŚ BAD â€” exposes internal sequence, no timestamps
{ "id": 42, "email": "alice@example.com" }
```

## SECURITY
- All endpoints MUST require authentication unless explicitly marked public.
- Validate and sanitize ALL query params and path params server-side.
- Rate-limit mutating endpoints (`POST`, `PUT`, `PATCH`, `DELETE`).

## FINALIZATION
- Ensure the OpenAPI spec (`openapi.yaml`) is updated to reflect any new or changed endpoints.
- Verify error responses match RFC 7807 format.
- Check that all list endpoints have pagination.
